            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How the Scotland tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator estimates your Scottish income tax and employee
                National Insurance for the 2025/26 tax year. It applies the
                Scottish income tax bands to your non‑savings, non‑dividend
                income and shows your net (take‑home) pay.
              </p>

              <h3>Scottish income tax bands (example 2025/26 structure)</h3>
              <p>
                The tool uses a banded system similar to the official Scottish
                rates:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Personal Allowance</strong> – normally £12,570,
                  reduced by £1 for every £2 of income above £100,000.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Starter rate</strong> – 19% on income just above the
                  allowance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Basic rate</strong> – 20% on the next slice of income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Intermediate rate</strong> – 21% on middle‑income
                  earnings.
                </li>
                <li><strong>Higher rate</strong> – 42% on higher earnings.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Top rate</strong> – 47% on income above the top
                  threshold.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Exact thresholds and rates are updated when new Scottish budgets
                are confirmed. Always check the latest figures on
                <a
                  href="https://www.gov.uk/scottish-income-tax"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener"
                  >gov.uk</a
                >
                or
                <a
                  href="https://www.mygov.scot/scottish-income-tax"
                  target="_blank"
                  rel="noopener"
                  >mygov.scot</a
                >.
              </p>

              <h3>National Insurance (employee Class 1)</h3>
              <p>
                If you tick “Include National Insurance”, the calculator
                estimates employee Class 1 NIC on your employment income. It
                uses the main thresholds and rates for the selected tax year and
                shows:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Total NIC for the year.</li>
                <li>Effective NIC rate as a percentage of gross income.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Pension contributions and student loans</h3>
              <p>
                Pension contributions are treated as
                <strong>relief at source</strong> for simplicity: we reduce your
                taxable pay by the chosen percentage before applying income tax.
              </p>
              <p>
                Student loan repayments are estimated using the standard
                thresholds and rates for:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Plan 1, Plan 2 and Plan 4 (Scottish) undergraduate loans.
                </li>
                <li>Postgraduate loans (Plan 3).</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator shows the impact of these deductions on your
                take‑home pay, but it is not a full self‑assessment tool.
              </p>

              <h2>Formulas used</h2>

              <h3>1. Adjusted personal allowance</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>If gross income ≤ £100,000:</p>
                <p>\( \text{PersonalAllowance} = £12{,}570 \)</p>
                <p>If gross income &gt; £100,000:</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Reduction} = \frac{\max(0, \text{Income} -
                  100{,}000)}{2} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{PersonalAllowance} = \max(0, 12{,}570 -
                  \text{Reduction}) \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Taxable income</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( \text{Pension} = \text{GrossIncome} \times
                  \text{PensionRate} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{AdjustedIncome} = \text{GrossIncome} - \text{Pension}
                  \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{TaxableIncome} = \max(0, \text{AdjustedIncome} -
                  \text{PersonalAllowance}) \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Banded Scottish income tax</h3>
              <p>
                For each band \( i \) with lower limit \( L_i \), upper limit \(
                U_i \) and rate \( r_i \):
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( \text{Slice}_i = \max\big(0,\; \min(\text{TaxableIncome},
                  U_i) - L_i \big) \)
                </p>
                <p>\( \text{Tax}_i = \text{Slice}_i \times r_i \)</p>
                <p>\( \text{TotalTax} = \sum_i \text{Tax}_i \)</p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. National Insurance (simplified)</h3>
              <p>
                For employment income, NIC is calculated on earnings between the
                main thresholds:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( \text{NIC} = \sum_j \big( \max(0, \min(\text{GrossIncome},
                  U_j) - L_j) \times r_j \big) \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>5. Take‑home pay</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \( \text{NetPay} = \text{GrossIncome} - \text{IncomeTax} -
                  \text{NIC} - \text{StudentLoan} - \text{Pension} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Limitations and notes</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Assumes a single source of employment income and standard tax
                  code.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not handle marriage allowance, blind person’s allowance
                  or other reliefs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not model savings and dividend income or Scottish
                  taxpayer status tests.
                </li>
